footballers = footballers.assign(Value=footballers['Value (M)'], Position=footballers['Preferred Positions'].str.split().str[0])

INFERENCE:
In the scatter plot matrix, we see that the plots ae seemingly random at first glance. When we take a deeper look, we notice that the lines formed by 2 distinct attributes are in fact positively related and fairly linear. The reason why it is not clear is due to the size of the markers being too large in addition to multiple outliers found in the dataset. There are over 17000 rows and thus, even a few hundred outliers can cause the visualisation to look dense and convoluted.
Almost all attributes are positively correlated and a few are negatively correlated (when the graph trend seems to move downward). The magnitude of correlation is between -1 and +1 with the negative extreme to be perfect negative correlation while the positive extreme is perfect positive correlation. The plots where there is no trend observed, the correlation value is closer to 0.

import matplotlib
matplotlib.use('Agg')
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from numpy.random import rand
from numpy import pi, arctan

def cface(ax, x1,x2,x3,x4,x5,x6,x7,x8,x9,x10,x11,x12,x13,x14,x15,x16,x17,x18):
    # transform some values so that input between 0,1 yields variety of output
    x3 = 1.9*(x3-.5)
    x4 = (x4+.25)
    x5 = (x5+.2)
    x6 = .3*(x6+.01)
    x8 = 5*(x8+.001)
    x11 /= 5
    x12 = 2*(x12-.5)
    x13 += .05
    x14 += .1
    x15 = .5*(x15-.5)
    x16 = .25*x16
    x17 = .5*(x17-.5)
    x18 = .5*(x18+.1)

    # top of face, in box with l=-x4, r=x4, t=x1, b=x3
    e = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (0,(x1+x3)/2), 2*x4, (x1-x3), fc='white', edgecolor='black', linewidth=2)
    # e.set_clip_box(ax.bbox)
    # e.set_facecolor([0,0,0])
    ax.add_artist(e)

    # bottom of face, in box with l=-x5, r=x5, b=-x1, t=x2+x3
    e = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (0,(-x1+x2+x3)/2), 2*x5, (x1+x2+x3), fc='white', edgecolor='black', linewidth=2)
    ax.add_artist(e)

    # cover overlaps
    e = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (0,(x1+x3)/2), 2*x4, (x1-x3), fc='white', edgecolor='black', ec='none')
    ax.add_artist(e)
    e = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (0,(-x1+x2+x3)/2), 2*x5, (x1+x2+x3), fc='white', edgecolor='black', ec='none')
    ax.add_artist(e)
    
    # draw nose
    ax.plot([0,0], [-x6/2, x6/2], 'k')
    
    # draw mouth
    p = matplotlib.patches.Arc( (0,-x7+.5/x8), 1/x8, 1/x8, theta1=270-180/pi*arctan(x8*x9), theta2=270+180/pi*arctan(x8*x9))
    ax.add_artist(p)
    
    # draw eyes
    p = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (-x11-x14/2,x10), x14, x13*x14, angle=-180/pi*x12, facecolor='white', edgecolor='black')
    ax.add_artist(p)
    
    p = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (x11+x14/2,x10), x14, x13*x14, angle=180/pi*x12, facecolor='white', edgecolor='black')
    ax.add_artist(p)

    # draw pupils
    p = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (-x11-x14/2-x15*x14/2, x10), .05, .05, facecolor='black')
    ax.add_artist(p)
    p = matplotlib.patches.Ellipse( (x11+x14/2-x15*x14/2, x10), .05, .05, facecolor='black')
    ax.add_artist(p)
    
    # draw eyebrows
    ax.plot([-x11-x14/2-x14*x18/2,-x11-x14/2+x14*x18/2],[x10+x13*x14*(x16+x17),x10+x13*x14*(x16-x17)],'k')
    ax.plot([x11+x14/2+x14*x18/2,x11+x14/2-x14*x18/2],[x10+x13*x14*(x16+x17),x10+x13*x14*(x16-x17)],'k')

# x1 = height  of upper face
# x2 = overlap of lower face
# x3 = half of vertical size of face
# x4 = width of upper face
# x5 = width of lower face
# x6 = length of nose
# x7 = vertical position of mouth
# x8 = curvature of mouth
# x9 = width of mouth
# x10 = vertical position of eyes
# x11 = separation of eyes
# x12 = slant of eyes
# x13 = eccentricity of eyes
# x14 = size of eyes
# x15 = position of pupils
# x16 = vertical position of eyebrows
# x17 = slant of eyebrows
# x18 = size of eyebrows

## These are modifiable depending on the scenario. For this exercise, these are the attributes.

In [50]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(11,11))
for i in range(25):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(5,5,i+1,aspect='equal')
    cface(ax, .5, *rand(17))
    ax.axis([-1.2,1.2,-1.2,1.2])
    ax.set_xticks([])
    ax.set_yticks([])

fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0, wspace=0)
plt.savefig('plot3.png', bbox_inches='tight')

INFERENCE:
The above 18 attributes shown in the preprocessing part of this visualisation is encoded as one of the parts on the human face. The mapping is provided in the comments above. We see that the faces with taller frame and lower part overlapping the other features of the face shows higher accelration and aggression. Similarly, we want someone with wider eyes, nose and lips as they represent better free kick accuracy, dribbling, crossing, etc. The larger the face and wider the seperation between features, the better the values of the palyer in the attributes mentioned above. Thus, we see that the player in row 3 column 4 seems to be best overall performer from initial observation. More analysis is needed to prove or disprove this.

In [53]:
for pp in range(5):
    dff = pd.DataFrame(dict(
        r = list(map(float, f.iloc[pp, :])) ,
        theta=['Acceleration','Aggression','Agility', 'Balance', 'Ball control']))
    fig = px.line_polar(dff, r='r', theta='theta', line_close=True)
    fig.show()

INFERENCE:
Here, we have plotted several star plots. To maintain simplicity, I have plotted the star plot for only five different players. The attributes (1) Acceleration, (2) aggression, (3) agility, (4) balance and (5) ball control are compared using this technique. After normalising the variables, the points are identified and plotted on the rays shown above. In doing so, we create a loop that allows us to comprehend each player from five different perspectives. We ideally want a player who excels at all five attributes or shows a good balance between each of these skills. Thus, we can say that player four seems to be most rounded player of them all.

finalplot = final.pivot("Age", "Club", "Overall")
ax = sns.heatmap(finalplot)

INFERENCE:
For a given football club, the age of the players are identified and for each corresponding age-club, we encode the overall performance of the player and colour the cell. We see that lighter the colour, better the performance while darker the colour, the worse the performance. We therefore conclude that the player from Real Madrid FC who is 32 has the highest performance value. This data had no time attribute and thus this plot could not be utilised to its maximum capabilities as the main advantage of pixel oriented representation of multivariate data is to depict data ranging multiple years or decades. For this scenario, we see the overall performance with respect to the club and the age of the player.
